1. cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) - The paper deals with operations on a set of sequences and characterizing orthology relations, which are topics that fall under discrete mathematics. 
2. cs.LG (Machine Learning) - The paper proposes a novel algorithm, {\sc Network-Popping}, which is used to compute a phylogenetic network. This algorithm may be of interest to the machine learning community. 
3. cs.DB (Databases) - The paper deals with representing orthology relations, which are often used in biological databases. 
4. cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) - The paper characterizes orthology relations in terms of natural properties, which may be of interest to the game theory community. 
5. cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) - The paper proposes a computational method for representing orthology relations, which may be of interest to researchers in computational science and engineering.
